Game of Thrones Bipartite Network¶

This notebook explores battles from the Game of Thrones universe using a bipartite network approach.

We connect characters (kings, houses) to the battles they participated in.

By projecting the bipartite graph, we can uncover:

  • Which Kings House were central across multiple conflicts.
  • How alliances and rivalries shaped the war network.

Dataset: Game of Thrones Battles and Deaths (Kaggle)

After loading the bipartite graph, we can project it to analyze relationships among characters based on shared battles.

✅ Battle projection built with 38 battles and 520 connections.

The Above image show the the Bipartite graph of the battles and the characters involved in them. Battles are shown in large red nodes, while characters are shown in smaller blue nodes. Edges are colored based on the role of the character in the battle: attackers are shown with orange edges, and defenders with navy edges.

✅ Island base network built with 37 nodes and 37 weighted connections.

We now implement a weighted island method to identify key battles within allegiance networks. We start with the battle network with edges to other battles with atleast one shared house in each and progress to 6. We see Island emeergings for key battles campaing in the series that shaped the story.

Our interesting level for shared houses is 4, as it highlights significant battles with the same belliegerents and pointing to strageic events that shape the story for instance the battles along the the northern shore then Theon betrays the Starks and captures Winterfell. The battles around the Riverlands signifying the turmiol during Robb's Starks uprising and the instability after the Red Wedding. We also see the isolated networks with the battles on the shield islands an Euron makes his bid for a bigger part of the 7 kigndoms.

We now take a look at unitpate graph amoun houdes to understand the alliances and rivalries that shaped the war network.

✅ Projected character graph created with 27 nodes and 107 edges.

✅ Attack projection: 27 nodes, 31 edges
✅ Defense projection: 27 nodes, 18 edges

For the Follwing analysis I further filtered the data to only include battles with known attackers and defenders, ensuring a more accurate representation of the conflict dynamics. And then I take a look at the the top 20 Attacker and Defenders through their connections in shared battles to understand any alligiences that developed.

So as we SubA attackers that were on the same side in battles with atleast 20 shared connections we see the following: Stark-Tully, Stannis-Free Folk, Lannister-Bolton-Frey, and as expected we see Frey inbtween the starks and lannisters as they were involved in the red wedding.

In the Defender network we see some diffrences notably the Strak Island now is linked to the Greyjoy line as they were involved in battles before Theon betrays Robb. We also see a clear alliance formed between the Lannisters -Tyrells-Boltons-Freys having cemented their power through the red wedding and the battle of the blackwater. Stannis and and the peoples north of the war have also a clear formed alliance as we know from their battles against the dead and the boltons.

We measured the degree and betweenness centrality of all characters and houses within the bipartite battle network. As expected, House Lannister and House Stark emerge as the most central actors, reflecting their dominance across multiple fronts of the war.

Joffrey/Tommen Baratheon (the Lannister-aligned crown) holds the highest degree and betweenness, underscoring the central role of the Iron Throne’s forces as both initiators and sustainers of conflict. Robb Stark ranks second in degree, illustrating his pivotal involvement in numerous engagements during the Northern rebellion. The Lannisters exhibit slightly higher betweenness than the Starks, meaning they serve as key bridges between otherwise separate clusters of battles — consistent with their extensive campaigns across regions (Riverlands, King’s Landing, and the Westerlands).

Smaller houses such as Greyjoy, Tully, and Frey appear with moderate to low centrality, indicating regional participation or alliance-based involvement rather than sustained warfare across multiple theaters. Overall, the centrality measures reinforce the narrative hierarchy of power: the Lannister–Baratheon bloc dominates the conflict structure, while the Stark coalition represents the main opposition force.

In the analysis of battles, the most central by degree — meaning those with the greatest number of connections to other battles through shared participants — are the Siege of Winterfell and the Battle of Deepwood Motte. This finding is somewhat unexpected, as both occur after the Red Wedding and are geographically isolated in the North. However, this result underscores the importance of remembering how connections are defined: a battle is linked to another when they share at least one participating house or commander. The prominence of these northern battles suggests that, even after the fall of House Stark, the struggle for control of the North remains structurally central to the network of conflicts. Additionally, several battles in the Riverlands also appear as highly connected nodes, reflecting how intertwined these engagements were leading up to and following the Red Wedding — collectively marking the collapse of Northern power and the consolidation of Lannister dominance.
